I opened a bug report in May 2017. It's not possible to update a property of GKE (one of GCP's most promoted services) through Deployment Manager. This works perfectly fine through the public API.

Google Cloud's Deployment Manager is one GCP service I would recommend NOT using. There are theoretical advantages native declarative infra frameworks (DM & cloudformation) have over public API based (terraform), but in practice TF is strictly better. What are some things he's done that you'd consider irresponsible?

yes, but elon maximizes both power and deliberately cultivated exposure. being such a powerful public figure carries concomitant responsibility. to be clear i agree with the underlying thesis that he is overly criticized in certain circles. (but also overly exalted in others.)

I'm not sure I'd go that far. The huge difference IMO is that Trump acts in bad faith. Elon has loudly had some arguably bad ideas, but I don't get the troll sense from him. A good measure of the arrogance that comes from wild success, but not necessarily malice.

But don't you think there are *so* many people in & above his power bracket that are *so* much less responsible with their power? That's what I don't understand. Musk has some big flaws, but he's also done more for green energy & transportation than arguably anyone ever.

Also, Musk seems to have grown to like the attention. He has too many of the negative traits that stereotype Silicon Valley - Burning Man, flirtation with misogynistic nerd culture, etc. Those have made him a riper target than, say, Bezos, who's legit evil but is also low-key.

Best I can tell, it's that even smart people seem to have a hard time with black-and-white thinking. Should any human be worth $20B? No. But does that mean everything that person does is automatically bad? Also no. But the latter opinion doesn't seem as universally held.
he's irresponsible with the power he has and deserves some of the flak, but I generally agree, it's virtue signaling in its lowest form
